{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":20508,"name":"Alan","username":"Alan","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/alan/{size}/783_2.png","created_at":"2017-08-30T12:15:24.219Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eHey there \u003cimg src=\"https://emoji.discourse-cdn.com/twitter/slight_smile.png?v=5\" title=\":slight_smile:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":slight_smile:\"\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIâ€™d like to know whatâ€™s the best approach to render pixel-art pixel-perfectly \u003cimg src=\"https://emoji.discourse-cdn.com/twitter/stuck_out_tongue_closed_eyes.png?v=5\" title=\":stuck_out_tongue_closed_eyes:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":stuck_out_tongue_closed_eyes:\"\u003e, with some simple math itâ€™s easy to map texture pixels into pixels on screen, or into 4 pixels and so on, but when your geometry isnâ€™t perfectly aligned to the pixels, you get different results depending on the position of them, I guess mostly due to rounding error in the sampler (with vertex imprecision accumulated). Iâ€™ve seen two different approaches for that, possibly the simplest one is snapping the nodes themselves to pixel-perfect positions, thatâ€™s what Nez does, but it obviously impacts the game logic, the other approach is using some kind of visual-only pixel snapping technique, which you could do in the GPU by snapping solely the vertices in the VS, but depending on the situation, if youâ€™re dealing with imprecise numbers (far from zero), you may get floating point precision problems like some vertices rounding down and some rounding up. Iâ€™ve also seen snapping on the PS on top of that, what sounds more complicated than it should to solve such a simple problem.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe idea here is to render a rather low-res texture and display it on screen, mapped proportionally to the screen pixels so pixel art looks good and is cheap to render.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eAny help on this? Thanks in advance! \u003cimg src=\"https://emoji.discourse-cdn.com/twitter/blush.png?v=5